ian, Chinese, and English, he then traces a series of encounters shaped by economic and geopolitical events from the Cultural Revolution, perestroika, and the June 4 massacre to the collapse of the Soviet Union, September 11, and the invasion of Iraq. In these encounters, Edmond tracks a shared concern with strangeness through which poets contested old binary oppositions as they reemerged in new, post-Cold War forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aComparative literature. 0aLiterature and globalization. 0aPoetry, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aamerican culture.  aamerican literature.  aavant-gard literature.  achinese culture.  achinese literature.  acomparative literature.  acontemporary literature.  acultural theory.  aglobalization.  aliterary theory.  amodernist literature.  apoetry.  arussian culture.  arussian literature.  aworld literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082324260340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823242627?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823242627423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823242627/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK